  glutamatergic neuron" src/ontology/cl-edit.owl | head -20                   
    733:Declaration(Class(obo:CL_0000679))                                    
    9721:# Class: obo:CL_0000679 (glutamatergic neuron)                       
    9723:AnnotationAssertion(obo:IAO_0000115 obo:CL_0000679 "A neuron that is 
  capable of some neurotansmission by glutamate secretion.")                  
    9724:AnnotationAssertion(oboInOwl:hasDbXref obo:CL_0000679 "WBbt:0006829")
    9725:AnnotationAssertion(rdfs:label obo:CL_0000679 "glutamatergic neuron")
    9726:EquivalentClasses(obo:CL_0000679 ObjectIntersectionOf(obo:CL_0000540 
  ObjectSomeValuesFrom(obo:RO_0002215 obo:GO_0061535)))                       
    9727:SubClassOf(obo:CL_0000679 obo:CL_0000540)                            
    9853:AnnotationAssertion(Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref "PMID:10600995")   
  Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref "PMID:34047341") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref
  "PMID:36774666") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref "PMID:37775311")             
  Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref "PMID:9728912") obo:IAO_0000115 obo:CL_0000695
  "A type of transient, early-born glutamatergic neuron located primarily in  
  the marginal zone (future layer I) of the developing cerebral cortex and    
  hippocampus in vertebrates. it is characterized by a bipolar morphology with
  an elongated soma, a single thick dendrite oriented toward the pial surface,
  and a long, thin axon that extends tangentially to form horizontal plexuses 
  across the cortical surface. It is important for the multiple developmental 
  processes including migration, dendritogenesis and synaptogenesis. It       
  typically undergoes programmed cell death following cortical maturation with
  species- and region specific patterns of survival. In mice, it is           
  predominantly observed in the hippocampal formation, particularly in the    
  stratum lacunosum-moleculare and outer molecular layer of the dentate gyrus 
  (van Bruggen et al., 2023). In contrast, in humans, a second morphologically
  distinct subpopulation emerges mid-gestation and persists postnatally, with 
  surviving cells observed in the cortical sulci and the hippocampus.")       
    9859:SubClassOf(obo:CL_0000695 obo:CL_0000679)                            
    13399:SubClassOf(obo:CL_0001031 obo:CL_0000679)                           
    23079:AnnotationAssertion(rdfs:comment obo:CL_0008030 "Consider using     
  glutamatergic neuron instead. Do note that not all glutamatergic neurons are
  excitatory and replacing excitatory neuron with glutamatergic neuron should 
  be done with caution.")                                                     
    29857:# Class: obo:CL_2000028 (cerebellum glutamatergic neuron)           
